    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#AccumulatorMotor</IRI>
        <Literal>Motor = motor + reductor</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#AccumulatorPulleyBeltSystem</IRI>
        <Literal>PulleyBeltSystem = 2 pulleys + 1 belt</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Component</IRI>
        <Literal>TO VERIFY TO DISJOIN BETWEEN:

- MACHINE COMPONENT
- PRODUCT COMPONENT</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#ConditionMonitoring</IRI>
        <Literal>From Polenghi 2022:

BFO:Process to monitor an AO:Artifact by measuring a specific phenomenon</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#CyclicPreventiveMaintenanceElapsedInterval</IRI>
        <Literal>Commento:

- migliorare il termine

From Montero et al. 2012 (TBN, noi abbiamo cambiato termine):

A COMSA: triggering event subclass related to preventive maintenance strategy. It is prescribed by a preventive maintenance plan. A recommendation based on fixed operation intervals or from fixed basic inspections triggers a maintenance action.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#DegradationProcess</IRI>
        <Literal>From IOF and Karray 2019:

A BFO:Process that results in the loss of ability to perform a BFO:Function.
The loss of ability of a component or engineering system to perform its required function.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#DegradationThresholdOvershoot</IRI>
        <Literal>Commento:

- anche con la predictive superi una threshold, solo che è predetta, mentre nella cbm NO PRED è attuale basata sul monitoraggio

From Montero et al. 2021:

A COMSA: triggering event subclass related to predictive maintenance strategy. It is prescribed by a degradation assessment module of a predictive maintenance system.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Deviation</IRI>
        <Literal>- valutare legame con &quot;non conformity&quot; come deviation of product quality</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Deviation</IRI>
        <Literal>general definition:

difference between requirements* and actual performance

* requirements of products (e.g. dimensional tolerances) and process (e.g. energy absorption)</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#ElectromechanicalFailureMode</IRI>
        <Literal>From Medina et al. 2014:

tipologie di guasto definite
Da migliorare:
- separazione hydraulic/pneumatic (già fatta)
- definizioni
- relazioni (vedere comunque Medina)

vedere comunque Nunez &amp; Borsato per tipologie failure mode (forse)</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Ent_bob_abou</IRI>
        <Literal>Coil in changing position (vertical)</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Ent_bob_cour</IRI>
        <Literal>Coil in current position (horizontal)</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#FailureCauseID</IRI>
        <Literal>TO BE VERIFIED AND EVENTUALLY RE-ALLOCATED</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#FailureMode</IRI>
        <Literal>From IOF:

Def. A BFO:Realizable Entity that is the UNK:Consequence of a MNT:FailureMechanism through which the MNT:StateOfFailue occurs</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#FailureModeID</IRI>
        <Literal>Originally as information:

From Montero et al. 2021

A CCO: Descriptive Information Content Entity that describes the cause of a failure mode. It is about a CCO: Cause that can lead to an OMSSA: Failure</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#FailureModeID</IRI>
        <Literal>TO BE VERIFIED AND EVENTUALLY RE-ALLOCATED</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Flow</IRI>
        <Literal>Class added in order to be able to infer the relation between the measured variable and the negative deviations of the non-measurable variable (Sofia and Julie)</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Function</IRI>
        <Literal>A function is a disposition that exists in virtue of the bearer’s physical make-up and this physical make-up is something the bearer possesses because it came into being, either through evolution (in the case of natural biological entities) or through intentional design (in the case of artifacts), in order to realize processes of a certain sort. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [064-001])</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Function</IRI>
        <Literal>BFO 2 Reference: In the past, we have distinguished two varieties of function, artifactual function and biological function. These are not asserted subtypes of BFO:function however, since the same function – for example: to pump, to transport – can exist both in artifacts and in biological entities. The asserted subtypes of function that would be needed in order to yield a separate monoheirarchy are not artifactual function, biological function, etc., but rather transporting function, pumping function, etc.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Function</IRI>
        <Literal>vedi bene IOF + vedere una tassonomia (forse CCO)</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#HealthAssessment</IRI>
        <Literal>Together with PrognosticAssessment

This may be excluded or not depending on the final goal of the ontology.
They could be excluded if the ontology is a mean to support maintenance analyses, whereas they are part of the ontology if we want to describe the maintenance domain as external viewer.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#InformationContentEntity</IRI>
        <Literal>consider relation &quot;isAbout&quot; with Continuant or Process</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Machine</IRI>
        <Literal>Out comment:

an asset that transforms the product</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#MaintenanceAction</IRI>
        <Literal>From IOF:

Def. A BFO:Process to perform work on an IOF:Component according to a MNT:Maintenance_Work_Specification.
One of more tasks necessary to retain an item in or restore it to a specified condition.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#MaintenanceProcess</IRI>
        <Literal>From IOF:

A BFO:Process comprised of MNT:MaintenanceAction to retain or restore an MNT:MaintainableItem to perform a BFO:Function.
All activities necessary to retain or restore the functionality of an asset.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#MaintenanceProcess</IRI>
        <Literal>With respect to norm 17007.

Maintenance processes could be classified into:
- maintenance action
- maintenance management
- maintenance support processes</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#MaterialArtifact</IRI>
        <Literal>To define the subclasses of artifacts, it could be useful to use general class axioms like:

product is an artifact and it bears a product role

the same for &quot;function&quot;?</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Nonconformity</IRI>
        <Literal>deviation</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Nonconformity</IRI>
        <Literal>non conformity equivalent = Deviation + don&apos;t meet Requirement</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
